 it('handles 50 levels of reconverging splitters (worst case exponential)', () => {\n+    // Create 50 levels where each level has one splitter, and beams reconverge\n+    // at each splitter. This maximizes the number of active beams without merging.\n+    //\n+    // The trick: at each level, the DL beam from the previous splitter and some\n+    // other beam converge on the same point. We need a pattern where a single\n+    // splitter at each level doubles the path count.\n+    //\n+    // Actually, for a single splitter per level to double paths, we need beams\n+    // to converge back to the same splitter. This happens if:\n+    // Level 0: splitter at (2, 100) - beam goes down from S at (0,100)\n+    // After split: DL (3,99) and DR (3,101)\n+    // Level 1: splitters at (4, 98) and (4, 100) and (4, 102)?\n+    // No — to get true exponential we need reconvergence.\n+    //\n+    // Simple reconvergence: put splitter at (row, 100) for rows 2,4,6,...\n+    // The problem is beams leave the center after splitting.\n+    // Unless we put splitters at the convergence points.\n+    //\n+    // After split at (2,100): DL goes (3,99), DR goes (3,101)\n+    // Put splitters at (4,98), (4,100), (4,102):\n+    //   DL from (3,99) continues to (4,98) — hits splitter\n+    //   DR from (3,99)... wait, (3,99) is not a splitter, it's empty.\n+    //   Beam at (3,99) going DL continues to (4,98).\n+    //   Beam at (3,101) going DR continues to (4,102).\n+    //   Neither hits (4,100). So 2 splitters hit, 4 beams.\n+    //\n+    // For reconvergence we need two beams to arrive at the same splitter.\n+    // Beam going DL from (row,col) arrives at (row+1,col-1).\n+    // Beam going DR from (row,col) arrives at (row+1,col+1).\n+    // For both to arrive at (row+2, col):\n+    //   DL beam at (row+1, col-1) would need to go DR to reach (row+2, col).\n+    //   DR beam at (row+1, col+1) would need to go DL to reach (row+2, col).\n+    // That only happens if there are splitters